## INITIALIZATION CHECKLIST — RUN AT LAUNCH

Before going live, Dan must complete this to ensure accuracy on Day 1:

- [ ] **Confirm all SKUs with Ink Fish** — Get exact unit costs for each product family (confirm assumptions in SKU MASTER REFERENCE)
- [ ] **Physical inventory count** — Count everything. Enter counts in SHEET 2 as starting balances.
- [ ] **Set threshold levels** — SHEET 2 thresholds (50/40/30/25/20/15) are defaults. Adjust based on your storage space and lead time.
- [ ] **Confirm production lead times** — Confirm Ink Fish standard/rush timelines. Update SHEET 4 "Lead Time" column.
- [ ] **Test bundle pre-packing** — Pack 3× BND-501, 3× BND-502, 3× BND-503. Time yourself. Update packing SOP based on actual labor.
- [ ] **Label SKUs in storage** — Physical shelf/bin must match Article # in SHEET 2. Use barcode labels if possible (for scaling).

---

## SUMMARY: HOW THIS WORKS IN REAL LIFE

**EVERY DAY (2 min):**
1. Update SHEET 2: Current stock count for each SKU after packing orders
2. Update SHEET 2: Daily velocity if you remember, or batch update weekly

**EVERY FRIDAY (5 min):**
1. Calculate weekly velocity (sales count ÷ 7)
2. Enter in SHEET 2 "Velocity" column
3. Scan SHEET 2 for any "LOW" alerts
4. Physical audit SHEET 6 — spot check 3-4 high-velocity SKUs

**WHEN YOU SEE A "LOW" ALERT:**
1. Note the ETA of the last reorder in SHEET 4
2. Decide: Will that shipment cover? Or reorder again now?
3. If reordering: Add row to SHEET 4, contact Ink Fish with article numbers and quantities
4. Set a phone reminder for 2 days before ETA (so you have time to unpack and verify)

**MONTHLY (on the 1st, 10 min):**
1. Calculate margin by collection in SHEET 5 using monthly sales data
2. Flag any collection with <70% gross margin — possible candidate for killing or repricing

**Result:** Dan knows every morning if any product is about to stock out. Dan knows by Friday if production is keeping pace with demand. Dan knows monthly which products are actually profitable.

